# Server Module Structure Guide

Use this for modules in `apps/*/server/src/modules/**`.

## Preferred Module Layout

Shared contracts:

```
apps/*/shared/src/modules/<module>/
├── <module>.constants.ts
└── <module>.schema.ts
```

Server module:

```
apps/*/server/src/modules/<module>/
├── <module>.db.ts
├── <module>.dto.ts            # optional for richer selects/outputs
├── <module>.repository.ts
├── <module>.service.ts
├── <module>.trpc.ts           # or *.router.ts for express endpoints
├── <module>.grants.ts         # when using BasePermissionService
└── <module>.jobs.ts           # optional workflow jobs
```

## Layer Boundaries

- `.repository.ts`: persistence only, no service imports.
- `.service.ts`: business logic and orchestration.
- `.trpc.ts` / `.router.ts`: transport only, delegate to service.
- `.jobs.ts`: worker entrypoints calling service methods.

## Composition Pattern

- Define classes in module files.
- Instantiate repositories in `apps/*/server/src/repository.ts`.
- Instantiate services in `apps/*/server/src/service.ts`.
- Keep module files free of global singleton wiring where possible.

## Auth and Permission Pattern

- Use `BasePermissionService` only when permission checks are actually needed.
- Keep grants in `<module>.grants.ts`.
- Guard action strings must match grant action names exactly.

## Workflow Pattern

- Queue payloads should be serializable primitives (`userId`, ids, input), not full request context objects.
- Prefer injecting service registries into workflow bootstrap over importing global service singletons inside jobs.
